'''Kumeuta''' or '''Kumeno Uta''' (久米歌・来目歌, "Songs of Kume") is a form of ancient Japanese {{ill|kayo|ja|歌謡|qq=draft}} found in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft}}. It is a {{ill|Gunka|ja|軍歌|qq=draft}} (military song) handed down by the {{ill|Kumebe|ja|久米部|qq=draft}} and traditionally performed during the {{ill|Kumemai|ja|久米舞|qq=draft}} dance.
== Overview == The songs are associated with the legendary expeditions of {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft}} to pacify regions such as {{ill|Yamato Province|ja|Yamato Province|qq=draft}}. According to the chronicles, the {{ill|Kumebe|ja|久米部|qq=draft}} sang these songs during battles against figures like {{ill|Eukashi|ja|兄猾|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yaso Takeru|ja|八十梟帥|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Eshiki|ja|兄磯城|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Nagazunehiko|ja|長髄彦|qq=draft}}. These songs, part of a repertoire used in court ceremonies, are preserved in eight instances in the *Nihon Shoki*, with six of them also addearing in the *Kojiki*.<ref>*Kojiki*, middlevolume, Emperor Jimmu section.</ref>
The songs were likely performed by members of the Kumebe, who served the {{ill|Yamato Court|ja|大和朝廷|qq=draft}} as both warriors and stewards. Their performances during post-battle banquets, accompanied by dance, became a form of courtly ritual affirming loyalty to the emperor. The martial themes of the songs align with the half-agricultural, half-hunting lifestyle of the Kumebe, expressed through the vigorous movements of the Kumemai.
The *Nihon Shoki* notes, "Even now, when musicians perform this song, they follow ancient customs regarding hand gestures and vocalization, preserving the traditions of old."
The Kumemai is documented as having been performed alongside foreign music at {{ill|Tōdai-ji|ja|東大寺|qq=draft}} in 749 (*Tenpyō Shōhō* 1) according to the {{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|qq=draft}}. While it fell into disuse after the reign of {{ill|Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado|ja|後土御門天皇|qq=draft}} (1465–1500), the Kumemai was revived during the {{ill|Daijōsai|ja|大嘗祭|qq=draft}} for {{ill|Emperor Ninkō|ja|仁孝天皇|qq=draft}}'s enthronement in 1818. Subsequently, it was performed during imperial enthronement ceremonies and at {{ill|Kigensetsu|ja|紀元節|qq=draft}} banquets in the {{ill|Toyomeiden|ja|豊明殿|qq=draft}} from 1878 to 1945.
== Analysis == According to {{ill|Takagi Ichinosuke|ja|高木市之助|qq=draft}}, Kumeuta conveys themes of determination and martial valor, as epitomized by lines like:
{{quotation|"In the millet fields, a single stalk of smelly chive—its root and shoots are tied together." (*Kojiki*)}}
and:
{{quotation|"Under the hedge grows a pungent pedder plant, stinging the mouth." (*Nihon Shoki*, Volume 3)<ref>*Nihon Shoki*, Emperor Jimmu pre-enthronement, fifth year of the dog, 12th month, 4th day.</ref>}}
Takagi suggests that these simple, everyday images express personal resolve and agency ("I shall not forget" or "I have starved enough"). These themes resonate with a vision of clan leaders who, while leading in battle, shared in the agricultural lives of their clansmen. The combination of long and short verses suggests the songs originated around the same period as the formation of structured poetry forms like {{ill|Chōka|ja|長歌|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Tanka|ja|短歌|qq=draft}}.
On the other hand, historian {{ill|Dobashi Hiroshi|ja|土橋寛|qq=draft}} argues that the songs are not merely expressions of the Kumebe's feelings but also affirm the loyalty of the Kumebe to the emperor. He highlights the hierarchical relationship wherein the Kumebe were subordinate to the {{ill|Ōtomo clan|ja|大伴氏|qq=draft}}, who in turn served the emperor.<ref name="Kume">Inoue Mitsusada, *Myth to History*, Chūō Kōronsha, 1965.</ref>
The {{ill|Song of the Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后伝説|qq=draft}}, a later document, records similar themes of the emperor directly leading troops and subduing rebellious clans during Japan's formative periods. While earlier interpretations posited a heroic age, modern research has clarified that a centralized monarchy had already emerged.<ref name="Kume"/>
== The Kumemai == The Kumemai is performed by two singers accompanied by instruments, including a {{ill|Ryūteki|ja|竜笛|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Hichiriki|ja|篳篥|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Wagoto|ja|和琴|qq=draft}}. Four dancers, clad in crimson robes and carrying ritual swords, execute the choreography.
The structure includes: * '''Opening Prelude''' (instrumental) * '''Entrance Songs''' (vocal and instrumental) * '''Dance Sections''', featuring chanted verses and instrumental interludes. * '''Closing Prelude''' (instrumental and vocal exit).
== Notes ==
